This is my 43! Pretty much 10 years since I had some frustrating health issues…

Today is my birthday and I’m reflecting on how much I have changed. It’s been a long road and plenty of challenges but has been WORTH it! 

I have a family history of gut diseases (cancer and Crohn’s), I had systemic Candida overgrowth and constant gut issues, cystic acne, inflammation, joint pain, brain fog, lethargy and extreme fatigue, I’m Alan ed hormones, heart flutters almost nightly, dramatic mood swings… I had to do something…

I went became vegan and raw in 2014 and haven’t looked back. As I continue to grow my microbiome and support my body, I realize how important it is to foster balanced and consistent habits instead of extremes. I used to rarely think about the future me because that was so far away, but here it is today. 

Thank you for being with me on this path and choosing compassionate choices for yourself too! 

No makeup before and after. Just fresh washed face and moisturizer. Before: age 32-33. After… age 43!

It’s my birthday today!! I’m 43 and wanna share a quiche yum recipe here! I also just shared a different recipe on my YouTube channel as well. The best birthday gift I could ask for is for you to choose compassion for the animals and your body!

The more variety the better in my opinion!! There are so many things we can eat and our gut bacteria loves it!

Sauce was for 2 people and simply:

2 small ripe avocados
1 date
1 lemon, juiced
2 cloves of garlic
2 ribs of celery
3 stalks of green onion
1/4 cup fresh dill
1 tsp miso paste
1 tsp onion powder
1/4 tsp mustard powder
1/4 tsp black pepper

Blended everything *except the fresh dill* with a very small amount of water until mega creamy. Once fully blended, add the fresh dill and pulse into the mix for 3 seconds. 

Enjoy!

Fiber feeds our microbiome and 97% of North Americans do not even get the RDA for fiber daily! Yikes!!⁠
⁠
Our microbiome digests the fiber which creates SCFAs (short chain fatty acids) and these fatty acids are incredibly beneficial for us!⁠
⁠
They not only are anti-inflammatory, but they are GOOD acids which keep pathogenic bacteria under control (which in turn balances the playing field inside our guts) and they also fuel our colonocytes (colon cells) and is a critical to helping to repair a leaky gut.⁠
⁠
One of the stars of the show is butyrate! To make butyrate though, we must eat fiber and feed the bacteria who create it. Building the gut can take time but it’s not the plant foods that are the problem, it’s a weak microbiome. So go SLOW and work WITH your microbiome, not against it!⁠
⁠

Cauliflower is quite a star!

Loaded with choline (typically quite low in a limited variety raw diet) and is likely a reason why those who go long periods under consuming choline rich foods end up craving eggs which are quite high in choline. 

In fact….. one medium head of cauliflower (easy to eat in a big raw chili or curry!) has DOUBLE the amount of choline in it compared to one egg. I find that many people forget about cauliflower (and other star veggies!!) and focus way too heavily on limited variety and/or super high fruit which leads many down a deficient road long term. Even a 3000+ calorie diet of just fruit variety still doesn’t hit the RDA for choline. Choline is essential for metabolism and used to synthesize phospholipids that are VITAL for all of our cell membranes structural integrity. 

Choline is also needed to produce an important neurotransmitter needed for memory, mood and other brain/nervous system functions along with modulating gene expression, lipid transport and cell membrane communication. 

Don’t miss out on this critically important ESSENTIAL nutrient (essential meaning we must eat it as our bodies don’t make it). 

Grab some cauliflower and make some raw chilies, curries or blend into dressings! My Soup ebook has soup base recipes and you can add cauliflower to your soups for a chunky yum!

Before I became a raw vegan I had a very skewed view of what a proper sized salad was and what were proper salad ingredients. My typical “salad” was a cup or two of lettuce, maybe 3 cherry tomatoes, and a couple other random veggies like a few coins of cucumber and some red onion. Worst even, I also added to this a mix of eggs, meat, croutons, olives and of course CHEESE! A salad was never complete without cheese in my mind. I assumed I needed to make my salad 'high protein" cuz why would I just eat "rabbit food"?⁠
⁠
My dressing was always high fat. Dairy or oil based and I figured that the random veggies would make up for it. My salads were seriously lacking in the fresh produce arena and overly saturated in the fat/animal products. The size was small but the calories were high and certainly not the same as what I eat now.⁠
⁠
When transitioning over to a raw diet, many people think a large salad is the same size as when they ate before, but forget that when you eliminate the meaty, cheesy animal products, oils, and random other items like croutons and corn chips, what you’re left with is a small snack at best. ⁠
⁠
I had to learn to REPLACE those undesired calories with desired ones. I had to replace my high fat dressings with low fat ones and make sure I had enough to satiate and get proper nutrition and variety. It was definitely different than what I knew my whole life, but worth relearning to experience the health I enjoy now!⁠
⁠

I heard a great quote the other day...⁠
⁠
"We either suffer the pain of discipline or the pain of regret"⁠
⁠
It rang so true. It can be very difficult to do the things we just don’t want to do... but really deep down DO want to do. ⁠
⁠
Some people dread the idea of spending another day chopping veggies in the kitchen, or waking up a little earlier, going to bed early and missing the next Netflix episode, or to get prepared for the next day. ⁠
⁠
Discipline is the act of doing what we REALLY want to be doing. If that is watching Netflix, do that. But if you REALLY want to eat healthier tomorrow, discipline yourself to make your lunch BEFORE you watch Netflix. Help yourself out and show up for YOU!⁠
⁠
Always remember, YOU are in charge! YOU make the choices. YOU choose your habits which determine your future! YOU are amazing and I believe in you!⁠

My top 5 favorite things about eating raw vegan foods?!

First up... I'm VEGAN for the animals. Which makes me happy and aligned with my ethics.

As for raw:

1) It’s hydrating! I still drink 2-3L of water a day (of course!) but I’m rarely ever thirsty anymore unless it’s a very hot sunny day or I’ve done a big hike, run or workout

2) Clean up is a breeze!! Because we don’t use oils, it’s so easy to rinse dishes after eating! No pots and pans to soak and scrub!

3) It’s easy!! Yes there are some recipes that take more time but so do some home cooked meals. I love that it’s mostly only chopping and blending and my favorite part is that I don’t have time and plan out dinner so nothing is over cooked and everything is perfectly ready all at the same moment. I don’t need to make a bunch of different things for a meal either, I can just enjoy a massively large salad and sauce or a smoothie! And if I want something REALLY fast? Just peel some fruit!

4) High fibre and easy digestion! It has been awesome working to build my microbiome over the last year. Lots of energy and I don’t feel heavy after eating. It’s so freeing! I used to always be tired and sluggish even if I had some healthy meals... I always found a way to justify SOMETHING that I knew wasn’t ideal.

5) It’s fun and creative. I eat such a wide variety and I have a blast creating new recipes and combining new flavors. It’s become my new reality. My old favorites were replaced with new ones and I don’t dread having to convince myself to eat healthfully anymore like I used to. The new habits have truly become my new reality.

What are some of your favorite things about eating raw meals? I know there’s many more but let’s share below!

There is no shame in not being all raw.⁠
⁠
Let me repeat: THERE IS NO *SHAME* IN NOT BEING ALL RAW!⁠
⁠
Countless souls try so hard to be all raw and when they struggle or fail, they feel shameful that they aren’t able to sustain it for whatever reason. Maybe they were under eating unknowingly, maybe they were trying to only eat organic and weren’t able to afford or get the variety. Maybe they caved to a craving because they went too long without eating or maybe they found themselves in some peer pressure.⁠
⁠
I choose to eat all raw because that’s what I WANT to be eating. It all boils down to what do you WANT, not what you feel you HAVE to do.⁠
⁠
Shame is a dark emotion and has no place in a healthier lifestyle. Instead of worrying about being perfect and pure according to the memes online or because someone said you had to do xyz in order to be fully detoxed etc, just think about adding more raw and think of the beauty that raw food gives you. Instead of feeling like you suck, remember how well you're doing and you feel when you choose something healthy. Instead of feeling ashamed that you aren’t perfect, feel incredible with the healthy choices you ARE making! That alone is a huge step in the right direction!⁠
⁠
It is certainly not about being perfect. It’s about eating more, choosing raw because you LOVE how it makes you feel and adding more and more if it until one day maybe that’s all you desire to choose.⁠
⁠

Let’s talk about why I personally feel (my own unpopular opinions!) that I never experienced a “detox” when I went raw vegan over 8 years ago.⁠
⁠
Some people have told me that the reason I never went through a major “healing crisis” or “detox” is because I didn’t fast and/or I didn’t do all fruit and ate too many greens.... which I disagree with.⁠
⁠
My theory?! I never experienced “detox” because the majority of “detox” symptoms are the same as under eating, which I was striving to not do. ⁠
⁠
I also do not believe that greens slow or stop detox. They FACILITATE IT! This is why when people have symptoms and they add lots of greens, the symptoms subside. They assume the greens are stopping detox but don’t see that the symptoms are gone because the greens help pull toxins OUT. ⁠
⁠
In all of my years working in the natural holistic health field (since 2001) & helping and consulting people with their health, the number one thing I was taught and learned about detoxing is that FIBRE and HYDRATION are the two most important factors, aside from eliminating the obvious obstructive foods and supporting phase I and II detox with adequate nutrition from whole plant foods.⁠

There are plenty of reasons why hair loss could be an issue for people following a raw diet... in fact... any diet for that matter!⁠
⁠
The top 3 things I see for raw vegans who deal with hair loss issues is ⁠
⁠
1) They are stressed out. Stress on ANY diet can be one of the major causes of hair loss ⁠
2) They do NOT eat enough. Even if they FEEL like they are, they most likely are not. Many people are SUPER surprised when they actually track their intake and find that it's still way too low. The body will struggle not only with healthy hair, but hormones, metabolism and other body functions when inadequate calories are consumed over a period of time. ⁠
3) They don't eat enough variety or mineral rich greens/veggies. This is also another big issues I have observed in those losing hair...⁠
⁠
It's easy to eat simply and under eat on a raw diet, but that doesn't mean it's ideal. We still need adequate calories and nutrition.⁠

How do we keep produce fresh?!⁠
⁠
1) We only buy what we KNOW we will eat.. not what we THINK we MIGHT eat! I used to do this a lot. I would get a big bag of apples thinking I would eat them all but I didn't. Now we just buy what we KNOW we will realistically eat within a week. This REALLY helps keep things fresh because we aren't letting things hang around long enough⁠
⁠
2) We shop more often. Again, only buying what we need, but buying fresh more often is way more pleasant⁠
⁠
3) We store the fruit on the counter (except berries) and veggie in the fridge (except tomatoes and avo - but they are fruit anyways!)⁠
You can find a produce temperature storage guide online (google!) and find out what temperatures and how long they can last, but overall, you can store most fruit at cool room temps and veggies should all be in the fridge, especially hardy greens like kale and cabbages, they like colder temps. Just takes practice to learn, as with anything in life⁠
⁠
4) Find out more tips in my latest YouTube video. You can find the link to my channel in my bio or watch my stories to find the tap link. ⁠

Prevention doesn’t really have an immediate noticeable “feeling” or “result” 

I get asked sometimes if I “notice” improvements while doing the things I do (like for example red light therapy or adding more variety to my diet to grow my microbiome, etc) and it’s a challenging question to answer because I feel amazing and I do what I do for my future self and to prevent, which doesn’t always have an immediate noticeable difference. 

Prevention also doesn’t mean “NEVER GET”… it just means “lessen the chances or slow the process” it’s not a guarantee obviously, but it’s a great thing to do, not always having to “see immediate results”

I do my red light therapy because I feel it’ll help the future me. I eat raw because I enjoy it and it’ll help the future me. I eat for my microbiome for them. I do things today that may not always come with dramatic immediate results, so my tomorrow isn’t as challenging as it might be had I not. 

We don’t always need an immediate result. That shows in the future. Over time, consistency, solid habit building and patience.

There are two very distinct mindsets around abstinence.

The first is that abstinence is restrictive. That the very idea that I avoid cooked food is limiting and dangerous. I could easily believe that cooked food is evil and toxic. I could believe that I’m not allowed it, that I cannot eat it. I could believe that I must stay raw or I’ll be sick. I could put stress and pressure on myself if I had a craving and feel guilt, shame and disappointment in myself. I could feel it’s not fair that I can’t eat certain things and I could feel that it’s very difficult to give up everything!

That feels pretty heavy doesn’t it? Can you relate?!

On the other hand, I actually feel that abstinence is freedom. I choose raw foods, not because I have to, but because I want to! It’s my choice and I have all the power. I no longer have the battles in my mind over what’s moderate or if I should or shouldn’t. I have clarity in my choices. I know what I want. I feel light, healthy, abundant, satiated and hydrated. I see my choices as beautiful, alive and vibrant. I focus on my goals. I feel proud of myself for making good choices and I always thank myself after eating for choosing health. I believe in abundance and variety on a raw diet. Sustainable and consistent nutrition! It’s my happiness! I certainly do not feel restricted! If anything, looking back, I had restricted myself from this freedom that I was so scared to achieve through abstinence.

So avoiding a certain consumable item can be either restrictive or freeing, it’s up to you. Giving up junky foods and animal products is something we already know we should do. It’s changing our perspectives that brings peace in that choice.

Do you HAVE to be raw to be healthy?⁠
⁠
I don't believe it's a prerequisite, but it's certainly a huge leap forward! I would much rather see someone eating MOSTLY raw and enjoying it, than to see them struggling to stay pure and perfectly all raw when they aren't ready. ⁠
⁠
I personally choose raw foods because I feel my best eating them. I do not believe that cooked food is poison or completely devoid of ALL nutrition because I am not a purist or absolutist. Of course you won't die right today if you eat cooked food (and by the way, we are all gonna die at some point, raw food isn't immortality), and you won't be malnourished because there is still nutrition in even the crappiest of cooked foods. ⁠
⁠
The question becomes, WHERE do you want to get your nutrition? Is there whole fiber? Was the food processed? What will best support my body and mental health? ⁠
⁠
The beauty is... YOU get to choose and YOU get to listen to your body to see how much raw YOU want to eat! Obviously I think it's amazing, so that's why I choose it, but plenty of people experience health improvements being high raw or even just eating more raw. ⁠
⁠

Why is dinner typically the most challenging meal of the day for most people?⁠
⁠
My thoughts as follows:⁠
⁠
1) People typically go too long without eating or don't eat enough throughout the day and end up hungry and ravenous at dinner time. The solution? Try eating MORE in the morning and at lunch and take fruit with you to snack on between meals. Get enough calories in so you aren't in a severe deficit come dinner time⁠
⁠
2) People tend to eat lunch at noon but then by the time they get home from work it's like 6-6:30 and they haven't eaten in over 6 hours. This will bring on MULTIPLE cravings, but not because we really crave those things out of nutritional necessity, we are just hungry and will literally eat anything⁠
⁠

⁠
4) Focus one day at a time. Go over your reasons and really strive to fuel up and focus on your goals!⁠

Why do I think most people shouldn't eat like me right away?

Well.. it's NOT because I don't think raw food is ideal

... and it's NOT because I don't think people can benefit from eating more raw foods...

It's because it honestly depends on where they are at! Here are some questions that I like to ask people who are new to raw food:

What is their microbiome looking like right now? 
How much fiber do they currently eat? 
What has their past diet been like? 
Were they breast or bottle fed babies? 
C section birth or natural? 
What is their history with antibiotic use? 
Do they still have an appendix? 
What is their sleep schedule like? 
Have they had a microbiome test done lately?
What symptoms do they experience when eating higher fiber?

There are so many ifs...

That's not to say that they can't start by going VEGAN! Start by eliminating animal products from the diet. Then start getting rid of processed foods and oils. THEN, slowly... add more fiber and more fiber varieities to build a stronger gut microbiome.

It takes years to build and it really depends on where starts out, but it's a worthy journey and we all know we can eat more raw fruits and veggies! It's my opinion that it's totally possible, WITH TIME AND PATIENCE, for most people to get to a high or all raw diet full of abundance and a wide variety of all raw plants, fruit, greens veggies, sprouts, microgreens and a small amount of omega 3 focused whole fats and herbs/spices galore! Just gotta start where you are!

Time and time again, struggling souls share with me their question of why they aren’t “good enough” or have enough willpower to overcome cravings...

One of my first thoughts are that they aren’t eating enough. It’s the main reason we have any cravings at all (symptom of hunger)...

One of the things I ask is, “What do you plan to eat today?”

The overwhelming reaction is “ummmmm.. hmmm”... they think about it for a moment, look at me with confusion and say that they have no idea. They scramble to take a wild guess at what they could have and right then I see a major cause to their struggles.

Lack of planning...

They haven’t thought at all about what to eat so they will be making decisions on an empty stomach, many times after restricting, skipping meals or going too long without eating.

I was there too. I used to wake up and have to rush to work. I’d grab whatever was around with caffeine to get me to my job. It was normally very high fat and small portions... if I even ate at all. By lunchtime I was ravenous and hangry. Irritable and tired. I did the same thing I did everyday. I just went with the moment. Same with dinner... very rarely was something planned. It was always hmmmm what do I feel like eating after a long day of not-so-great choices?

A successful day begins the night before. 

If you’re having issues with this, take a minute (it really only takes a minute or two!) and WRITE DOWN EXACTLY what you will eat tomorrow. Adjust your schedule if you’re able to (prep lunch the night before, or get up earlier, etc) and go to sleep with your plan in mind. 

Wake up, go over your day again and this time TAKE ACTION! 

When you plan out your meals, you know exactly how the day is going! We have calendars and schedules to keep meetings with others and get stuff done. We need to treat our meals and ourselves the same. All it takes is a quick moment to think of what you’ll have. It brings structure and peace, knowing you have that plan, setting up to succeed!

Why do I eat 2 salads a day instead of mostly all fruit all day?⁠
⁠
As much as I LOVE fruit, I also LOVE and appreciate veggies, greens, and sprouts for their wider fiber variety and nutrition profile. Fruit is not, in my opinion, better than vegetables. They are equal to me and therefore I need to eat MORE of the veggies to make up for the lower calorie density of them.⁠
⁠
When I first started my raw journey up in Canada, it was more challenging to get really good ripe fruit most of the year so I naturally defaulted to more salads due to cost and availability despite the internet telling me that I had to be fruitarian and only eat fruit because it was the only food for us...⁠
⁠
Glad I didn't!⁠
⁠
I feel that the huge amount of greens and veggies that I ate and still do eat, has helped me to stay raw, and to thrive on this diet. I didn't have detox symptoms and not because greens and veg slow detox, but because they HELP facilitate it! ⁠
⁠
I also think that the vast variety of things I ate besides just fruit was helping my gut to slowly build over the years, balancing out my microbiome and fighting off the excessive undesirable things like candida that I battled with for 15 years!⁠
⁠
Find out more about why I eat 2 salads a day in my latest video I just posted on YouTube to watch!! You can find the link to my channel in my bio or watch my stories to find the tap link. ⁠

⁠

We might wish for things to be easier or different but we really just have to start creating these new habits right now in order to notice the difference. ⁠

I wouldn’t say “no one” because that’s an absolute, but we get the core of what he’s trying to convey….

Prevention is an interesting thing to me. People seem to think “prevention” means “never get” but really, it means “lessen the chances of” 

Also… prevention doesn’t always come with dramatic and immediate results. Making changes can change how we feels yes, but not every change comes with noticeable assumed results. Expecting that we SHOULD notice something can sometimes cause us to stop doing the exact thing that is preventing stuff later! Sometimes prevention isn’t noticed until years down the road. 

A great example is my microbiome. I have great digestion and I’m not looking to “notice” a result. I choose to build my microbiome because although I don’t notice something TODAY or something at all, it’s about my future. I don’t have to notice something to know it’s probably a good idea. 

Being proactive, making changes and doing the work may not always be glamorous and instant but it sure can very well pay off in the end!

The word "prevent" doesn't mean NEVER GET...⁠
⁠
It means "to greatly lessen the changes of it occurring"⁠
⁠
Some people think that just by eating a raw diet, they will never get any illness whatsoever, and also hold those who follow this diet to the same standards⁠
⁠
This sets us all up for unmet expectations and disappointment. ⁠
⁠
Following a vegan or raw vegan diet doesn't mean we will never get certain illness.. it helps to PREVENT them, meaning that it greatly reduces our chances of potentially not getting them, but there are also no guarantees" ⁠
⁠

Being healthy can be hard. But being sick and feeling blah is also hard. Choose your hard.⁠
⁠
When I look back on my life, it was HARD to be where I was. It was hard to deal with constant cystic acne and skin inflammation. Trying to cover it with makeup was even worse. Not feeling comfortable in my own body, not having adequate energy, frustrates with constantly painful joints and feeling trapped by my secret food addictions. THAT was hard!⁠
⁠
The difficulty that was created from my unhealthy choices was what made me want to change. Looking at changing my lifestyle seemed hard as well. I had to learn how to silence my cravings, try new recipes, do more food prep, shop more, deal with social situations etc. I had to choose my hard.⁠
⁠
Funny thing is, looking back, all the diet change stuff that I THOUGHT was hard, I actually realize was just inconvenient. Even though it was tasty and EASY to choose whatever I wanted, it only lasted a few minutes and the hard life reality returned.⁠
⁠
Nothing compares to the freedom I feel now, there’s no way I could go back! Plus... mangoes or raw lasagna like in this picture... are certainly not hard to eat!⁠

LUNCH PREP TIPS:⁠
⁠
1) Do all the prep work in the morning! That’s when we are typically the freshest and have the most clarity and energy. When we wake up in the morning, our desires to eat healthfully for the day are typically at their strongest so prepping everything you can in that state is a great bonus!⁠
⁠
2) Make an extra double batch of dressing so you have some for after work when you’re tired or stressed and just want to get take out or throw something in the oven.⁠
⁠
3) Take fruit with you for snacks!⁠
⁠
4) Don’t forget to take your bowl, fork, a napkin and water if you need to rinse after eating.⁠
⁠
5) Dress half of your salad for lunch and eat the rest after work before you go home so you aren’t driving home hungry! That will help a lot with healthy evening meal choices.⁠
⁠
6) Pack everything g in a cooler bag with a freezer pack to keep things cool.⁠
⁠
7) If you can’t prep in the morning, make extra at night and prepare for the next day. Planning equals success!⁠
⁠
8) Get my ebooks and try out some fun new recipes!!⁠

So we are 1 month into the new year... ⁠
⁠
I used to say that I’ll start on New Years day... or on Monday or next week... but New Years, Monday and "next week" came and I wasn’t prepared, I failed to plan daily or I would start and after a few days I was already struggling so I would give up and start the cycle again.⁠
⁠
The year continued on and....⁠
⁠
I used to say it will be easier in the summer when fresh food is better and I just needed warm food in the winter but summer came and there were holidays, barbecues, beach parties, vacations and road trips and suddenly I was struggling again.⁠
⁠
I used to say I’ll start after that special event, so and so’s wedding, my sister’s birthday party or that next Sunday family reunion but was never able to get back to healthy choices after because there was always another event.⁠
⁠
I used to say that it would be easier to eat healthy if I just worked from home, but once I was working self employed at home... it was even harder because I didn't have to take a break or I could just order take out anytime I wanted even if the fridge was RIGHT THERE with healthier food in it...⁠
⁠
There is ALWAYS gonna be another work dinner, another get together, another holiday meal, another winter, another summer, another date night, another stressful workday in need of comfort. ALWAYS!⁠
⁠
So every day is an opportunity to change. There is no better time to start now. There will always be future challenges. Plan to overcome and you can succeed!⁠

Loaded up on sunchokes for a while - I really enjoy adding them to almost anything. They are one of the highest sources of inulin (along with chicory and endive family, jicama, garlic, onion and asparagus just to name a few) which is a powerful prebiotic food source for the microbiome.⁠
⁠
My mother's side of the family has a history of gut disease. Colon cancer (my mother had) and Crohn's disease (my uncle, her brother, passed away from complications when I was 10) run strong and I want to do anything I can to keep my gut healthy. So as a baby that was not breast fed and then struggling most of my adult life with candida overgrowth, gas, bloating, IBS symptoms and leaky gut, I have made it a focus to learn more about the gut and this is a big reason why I am so passionate about it.⁠
⁠
I eat a different diet that most raw foodies because I value variety. I don't eat "simple" meals with only 1-5 ingredients. I don't follow food combining “rules”. I don't want to not challenge my gut like I challenge my muscles to GROW and STRENGTHEN. I eat HUGE variety because I see now how important that is for building the gut. I don't eat only fruit either because as much as fruit is amazing, it's not the ONLY thing to eat. Veggies, greens, sprouts, roots etc are all so important in their own right and I feel like they get overshadowed by fruit when they should be a team treated equally. High five for vegetables too!⁠

Sometimes I wonder where I would be if I hadn’t changed….

Going raw vegan completely changed the trajectory of my life. Not only health wise but over the last 8.5 years so much has happened because of that initial choice. I never would have met the love of my life if I didn’t write my first raw meal plan and start a social media presence. I only started that because I went raw. I also immigrated to the USA in 2019 at age 39. I was born in and lived in Alberta Canada until then. I never woulda done that had I not met Nate (and I met Nate cuz I was raw). I used to be a professional photographer and I used to work as a shipping receiving manager at a big health store. I currently create recipes and help people online to eat more raw plants. I explore more nature (thanks to Nate haha) but my body isn’t in pain daily from something. 

I dealt with gut problems, skin issues, hormones imbalanced… gut disease runs in my family so I’m hyper aware of the microbiome science and health. My mother had colon cancer and her brother, my uncle, died with Crohn’s. I was headed down a difficult road and was constantly tired, exhausted, hurting somewhere or with a cold/flu, or bladder/yeast infection. I also had issues with insulin on top of it all. 

Where would I be had I not made that choice in 2014?! I’ll never know… but statistics show a probable outcome. At 43…. I may not even be here. Really puts mortality in perspective…

The 5 foods that I eat now that I didn’t eat before!

I’ve been following a raw diet for 8.5 years now and only in the last year have I started adding new raw options that I never ate before!

I added these to provide strength and variety for my Microbiome, which has paid off in healthy gut test results!

1 • Sunchokes: otherwise known as Jerusalem Artichoke. I actually never ate one of these until moving to Vegas... at age 42! They are 30% inulin and an epic feast for the gut! We use them almost daily, grated in a salad, frozen and thawed in veggie dishes (as pictured here - recipe is in the bundle in our Make it Raw ebook - link in bio @rawfoodromance) or even tossed into a dressing!

2 • Endive/Chicory: I ate these rarely just cuz but always found them bitter. Now I’ve been enjoying them near daily shredded in salads and I have been LOVING the bitters!

3 • Fennel & Fennel seeds: One if my fave additions! Fennel seeds every night on my salad. Fennel seeds are great for digestion in general!

4 • Asparagus: Another neglected veggie rarely eaten on a raw vegan diet. I never ate asparagus raw until now. We buy bunches of organic asparagus and chop to freeze or freeze dry it and add to marinated veggies and chunky things like curries, Chilis and marinaras.

5 • Pears: I always loved pears but never really had them as center stage in my diet. I have been recently adding them in and aiming to enjoy them a few times per week!

What new fresh produce have you been adding lately?

The gut isn’t “healed” when we eliminate fiber and variety. It’s healed when we are able to digest fiber and variety. 

I was listening to a podcast on Rich Roll last night from one of my fave gut docs Dr. Bulsiewicz and he said something profound that I agree with and have thought about for a while now. He said “not everything that feels good is good for us” 

He was referring to people who eliminate or greatly reduce fiber (carnivore/juice feast, etc) and suddenly “feel better” so they assume the fiber was the problem. But just because it feels better, doesn’t mean it’s ideal because as soon as they add higher fiber back, their symptoms return, many times worse than before because the gut starts to atrophy with the low to no fiber intake. This is problematic because they claim it’s healing but in reality, long term, it’s an illusion. 

He says that a truly healed gut is able to digest all of the fiber variety that one could eat. It’s like the low carb thing for diabetes. It’s not the absence of sugar that make one healed, it’s the ability to eat and use sugar properly that’s the sign of balance. 

He was asked “how do you know your gut is healed” and he replied “when you can digest all the fiber”. That means eating it. Gut growth can be uncomfortable by it’s akin to physio therapy after an accident or coma. Or building muscle. It causes soreness. It takes time. It’s challenging. We don’t say “the gym made my muscles sore so I’m never going to the gym again” 😂 so why are we not challenging our guts?! Food for thought! It’s never too late to start! Starting and working on progress is better than never doing anything be aide you want to be “perfect” 

We don’t expect t to be fluent in another language overnight. Or be able to play intricate pieces by heart with a new instrument we just picked up yesterday… we understand those things take time and practice… same goes for our HABITS! They do NOT change overnight or with one try. They slowly change over time with repetition the more often you practice a new language, an instrument and YOUR DAILY HABITS, the better you get at them. So just start! 

When it comes to a raw diet people tend to think that if they aren’t 100% perfectly raw, there’s no point in even trying, but what if you just started aiming to eat more raw and practiced making raw choices more often until one day it’s your new reality?! It’s much better to practice and grow than to never try at all because it’s not “the right time” or “it’s too cold here” or “when my partner is on board it’ll be perfect” or “next month I’ll be able to focus more to be perfect” etc. We don’t need to wait for some perfect day to practice new eating habits because we eat every day. Every single day we have multiple opportunities to make different choices and practice new habits. What will you continue or what will you start to build?! The choice is yours.

Did you know that ONE ounce of sunflower microgreens has 6 mg of iron?! 

🤯 

One ounce is just about a full cup of them chopped. That’s it! For 6mg iron?! 

The daily RDA for menstruating women is 18mg. Men only need 8mg a day. 

So just one cup of sunflower microgreens provides a third of my daily intake for iron, not to mention the countless other foods that have small bits too that add up. 

Eating them with citrus or something else high in vitamin C like bell peppers or tomatoes helps absorb the iron. Chew them thoroughly and add them to anything! Salads, wraps, grind them up in raw burgers, taco grounds, put some on top of a raw soups, curries or chili. So many options, you can even just eat them straight as is!!

Get more iron by including more sunflower microgreens. Grow your own too for pennies per serving.

I was asked today how I stay motivated after 8.5 years on this diet and to be honest, it’s no longer motivation. It’s become a habit. 

Motivation can get us started but it habit that keeps us going. It’s habit that continues on when one has struggles. Habits are the most powerful and strong behaviours we have as humans and changing them is the real challenge. 

I haven’t had to motivate myself to eat raw in years. I can’t even remember the last time I needed motivation because habit has taken over and I just do it. Yes the good is good and yes I feel great but that’s not what ultimately keeps me choosing this. It’s just habit.

Habits are formed through repetition. I just repeated the new habit I wanted enough times that it became my new reality. Anyone can change habits if they really want to! It’s hard on the beginning but so worth it when they solidify!

Cruciferous vegetables are a group of plants that belong to the Brassicaceae family, and they include popular vegetables such as broccoli, cauliflower, radishes, Brussels sprouts, kale, mustard greens, arugula, bok choy and cabbage. These vegetables are rich in nutrients and have been associated with various health benefits including feeding the gut microbiome and helping the liver with phase 2 detox.

Rich in vitamins and minerals: Cruciferous vegetables are an excellent source of vitamins C, E, and K, as well as folate, potassium, and calcium.

Several studies have also shown that cruciferous vegetables contain compounds that may help to prevent cancer. For example, sulforaphane, a compound found in broccoli and other cruciferous vegetables, has been shown to have anti-cancer properties. Broccoli sprouts are one of the best sources! 

Cruciferous vegetables may also help to reduce the risk of heart disease. They contain fiber, which can help to lower cholesterol levels, and potassium, which can help to regulate blood pressure. They also contain compounds that have anti-inflammatory properties, which can help to reduce inflammation in the body. Chronic inflammation has been linked to a range of health problems, including heart disease and cancer.

Cruciferous vegetables are rich in fiber, which can help to promote healthy detox, digestion and prevent constipation. They also contain enzymes that can aid in the digestion of food and are powerful helpers in our natural daily detox pathways. Wanna detox?! Eat more cruciferous veggies! 

Cruciferous veggies for the win!! This salad has broccoli, cabbage, Brussels sprouts and kale with a delicious creamy Caesar yum drizzled atop.

It’s been about 8.5 years following this raw vegan thing and I’m CONSTANTLY learning and changing how I think and how I believe about food, myself and life.⁠
⁠
I really love where I’m at right now. I’ve built a very strong gut microbiome and I’m enjoying so many more plant foods in my diet that I believe have taken things to a new level like fennel seeds, sunchokes, asparagus and more inulin rich things. Fermented foods have been a blessing and we enjoy them daily. Sprouts and microgreens have taken center stage. Fruit is always a base and highly valued but so are greens, cruciferous and other veggies.⁠
⁠
Body image and beliefs shift and change over the years and I’m loving the VERY relaxed enjoyment of my life instead of during the early days when I was trying to be pure and perfect, stressed over who thought I wasn’t doing it right or what I should do next to be accepted by others and their certain belief systems.⁠
⁠
The top things I’ve learned:⁠
⁠
• Be consistent⁠
• Eat enough⁠
• Eat a wide variety of plant foods⁠
• Release perfectionism (I know easier said than done but worth working on!)⁠
• Embrace change⁠
• Body acceptance no matter what shape or age. Loving myself through it all and enjoying each day as a gift instead of feeling like I have to change in order to be accepted or good enough.⁠
⁠
Each of us are on our own journeys and changing at our own pace. Accepting where we are is an ongoing learning experience.⁠

Steps to new healthy habits⁠
⁠
First: PLAN! Go through what you plan to eat. Takes 30 seconds in the morning or before bed. If you don’t plan what to eat, most likely you will be “winging it” and just eat whatever. Plan what you REALLY want to be eating and that you enjoy eating.⁠
⁠
Second step: EAT! Eat real food. If you don’t eat enough you are likely going to feel challenged, hungry and frustrated. Dinner is going to be difficult as well. Eat up! You deserve to be nourished!⁠
⁠
Third step: FOCUS. Go over your reasons for your new habit changes. The animals, the planet, your health, your family’s health, being an example, feeling better/great, etc. Focus on your whys and focus on the positive things about your new habits. Find the JOY in your new habits.⁠
⁠
And lastly: CONSISTENCY. It either keeps you where you are or gets you where you wanna go. Where do you wanna go? Consistency is the key to success.⁠
⁠

When travelling as raw vegans, we MUST plan. Actually… gotta plan daily! Planning might be boring but it’s one of the biggest keys to success. Plan! 

What are you planning to have today? When I ask people this question, nearly all of them have no idea. The top answer I get is “oh I haven’t thought of that” which means they will be winging it and choosing in the moment which may not always be the best choice they could make. Share in the comments what you plant to eat today, and if you’re seeing this at night, what do you plan to eat all day tomorrow. Get proactive and write it down. Studies show that those who physically write down their plans and goal actually succeed at accomplishing them more than those who didn’t. 

Also…. Yes I know tempeh is cooked before fermentation but I consider fermented foods to be raw regardless of them being cooked or not. I care more about the food being ALIVE and full of bacterial and enzymatic life, which is true for UNoasteurized fermented foods. Tempeh isn’t a staple but if we can find it unpasteurized, we will enjoy! P.S. Yes there is tempeh on this and yes I know to make tempeh there beans are cooked before fermenting. I consider fermented foods (regardless of their pre-fermented cooked or not cooked status) to be ALIVE and LIVING foods as long as the finished product is UNpasteurized like this tempeh we got in LA. It’s very rare to find unpasteurized truly alive tempeh unless you make it yourself so when we do find it UNpasteutized…. We get some! I consider unpasteurized ferments to still be a living food which has its place in a raw diet because it’s ALIVE and full of enzymatic and bacterial life!

Common questions I’ve been getting:

1) What trays are you using?! DM me for a link.

2) How many wraps does one tray make? One wrap cut in half. They are VERY filling!

3) They don’t get soggy? I have a special technique as you see here.. First, the wrap itself must be completely dry. Secondly, a TINY bit of sauce on the wrap with a barrier of lettuce helps keep wet ingredients like tomatoes and cucumbers from soaking the wrap. Thirdly, the wrap is quite large so it’s less likely to be soaked by ingredients. 

4) How long do these wraps last?! On the tray if FULLY dry, they can last about a week but they can get a wee bit dry around the edges by them. If you peel the wrap and fill it, they can last about 3-5 days depending on what you put in them. We took some hiking after we filled them 3 days ago and they were perfect. Even better flavour too cuz they had a chance to marinate.

Answers to more common raw wrap questions:

1) Are the recipes just for the wraps? Nope! Each full wrap recipe (there’s 33 in this ebook coming soon) has a recipe for the wrapper, a recipe for the matching filling, a recipe for the sauce (and other spreads if needed) and optional toppings etc. 

2) What equipment do we need to make these? A blender, a dehydrator, silicone dehydrator trays, a spatula, a knife and a cutting board! Deli paper is also nice to wrap them for next days fridge storage.

3) Are they low fat? This question is an interesting one because anything can be low fat if consumed in appropriate amounts. The term “low fat” actually means the fat % of all the calories across your whole day. Nuts and seeds still have their place on a low fat diet. These wraps recipes have each 1 tbsp of flax or chia omega 3 rich sources and a few have an extra tbsp of tahini but that’s it for the wrapper. As for how many you eat, what you put inside and how much high fat sauce you use is totally in your hands. I follow a low fat diet and I eat all these wraps but I also eat a huge amount of fruit and veggies as well.

Common wrap questions:

Q • Why not just use a tortilla or wheat wrap? 
A • Cuz I prefer eating whole fruits and vegetables… not cooked grains, oil and who knows what other ingredients they put in those….. Plus these are creative and bring more fiber variety. I don’t have to eat what everyone else is eating in order to be accepted. 

Q • Is there coconut in the wrapper?
A • Nope! None of the wrappers have coconut. They also don’t have oil or tree nuts. Just chia or flax with psyllium. They are considered low fat wraps. Only 1-2 tbsp fats per wrap! The only recipe containing coconut in my ebook is the quiche filling for the breakfast burrito.

Q • Will this book be in print?
A • Eventually yes. It’s a big project to reformat the ebook into print so it’ll take a while. I’m hoping late summer or early fall but no guarantees! I’ll share when it’s available though. 

Q • Do I need a dehydrator?
A • Yes. These recipes were formulated for a dehydrator. They are made at 115F with adequate airflow (fans) in the dehydrator. Ovens are enclosed and too hot, risking them turning into crackers. You can try… but having the oven on for 12 hours with it cracked isn’t safe or cheap… unless your oven has a dehydrator option. just get a dehydrator. You can find them used or refurbished or get new. 

Q • Is your ebook just wrapper recipes?
A • Nope! There are 33 wrap themed recipes that each  include the wrapper, a matching filling, a matching sauce (or 2 sometimes) and suggested toppings!

Q • Where can i get the recipes?
A • In my new ebook called Hand Salads! Link in my bio!

Wrap filling tips:

If you’re making a Hand Salad to wrap for the next day (or even day after as well) you’ll wanna stick to dry ingredients to help avoid soggy wraps. These wraps are a lot like regular wraps and they can get soggy if you use wet ingredients. I’ve had my fair share of soggy wheat or tortilla wraps in my day. I’m not a fan. 

If you’re wrapping for future enjoyment, avoid wet ingredients like wet lettuce, soft lettuces (soft lettuce isn’t as enjoyable next day), tomatoes (biggest one to avoid!), watery sauces, cucumber, sauerkraut and things like pickles. If you are putting sauerkraut or pickles in a later wrap, dry them off and squeeze out as much excess water that you can.  Stick to ingredients like stronger lettuces (romaine is a good one), shredded cabbages, ribboned carrots, microgreens, sprouts, seed or nut cheese and red onion. Also dehydrated veggies patties work really well in future wrapped hand salads too!

However… if you’re wrapping a wrap to eat right away in that moment, you can be pretty open to all kinds of fillings so put whatever you like in, including tomatoes, and eat up that deliciousness!

You don’t need to be a raw vegan to reap the incredible benefits of incorporating more raw plants into your diet. 

By embracing the wonders of raw foods, we can unlock a world of nutrition, enhance overall health, 

nurture the gut microbiome, and enjoy the abundance of fiber and new flavors.

Raw plants are bursting with vital nutrients and hydration. 

The gut microbiome plays a pivotal role in our well-being, influencing everything from digestion to mood. 

Raw plants are rich in prebiotic fibers that fuel the growth of beneficial gut bacteria. 

More plant variety also builds a stronger gut over time. 

This, in turn, can enhance digestion, boosts nutrient absorption, and promotes a healthy immune system. 

Our microbes release important phytochemicals like polyphenols when they break down the fiber. 

They also create anti inflammatory short chain fatty acids which balance the gut environment, ward off pathogenic bacteria and provide fuel for our liver, muscle and colon cells. 

Not only that, fiber also the helps regulate blood sugar levels, bind to cholesterol, promote satiety and more!

One of the joys of incorporating more raw plants into your diet is the culinary adventure that awaits you. 

Expand your palate. Try new things. It’s okay to explore and prepare our food differently!

So you don’t NEED to be a raw vegan to enjoy more raw food. Have fun!

What’s better…

A) Getting online as a newbie to raw and learning all kinds of scary things about food like, cooking is evil, this food is toxic or “not for humans” or that ferments are bad or maybe hearing that we lose our spirituality if we don’t eat super pure raw or that we will never heal unless we do exact specific restrictive and rule laden protocols. Being guaranteed results that may never occur no matter how “perfect” you are, being gaslit if you don’t experience said guarantees, and being scared or having even slight anxiety to buy, eat or do anything that doesn’t align with complete purity. Ending up following restrictive advice and finding yourself with more digestive and stress than what you started with…

Or…

B) You find raw food fascinating and learn more positive attributes to every new food you incorporate. You enjoy the flavors and variety of raw plants because you actually love them. You have fun experimenting with new recipes and foods but aren’t stressed if you aren’t absolutely perfectly raw every day. You eat enough and explore variety. You choose to eat raw foods for no other reason than they feel good and you genuinely want them. You choose out of freedom. You are in control and you make your own choices and path logically, not in an absolutist mindset. You work with your own gut and gradually add more raw until you find a spot with love and peace. You no longer choose out of fear and stress. 

There’s a lot of absolutism and lofty guarantees out there. Be aware and remember that comparison and perfectionism are forms of stress. Use logic and discernment and choose out of joy and love. 

Also remember that not one person has all the answers.

We focus so much as a society on this or that and absolutes that we have a harder time flowing with the consistency of life than the hard line extremes!⁠
⁠
One specific one that comes to mind is the whole idea of "never"⁠
⁠
"I can NEVER eat cooked food again!"⁠
"I'll NEVER enjoy that for the rest of my life"⁠
"I can NEVER do this or that"⁠
⁠
Never is a really deep word for our minds to comprehend and this mindset can cause intense struggles with the new habits we are trying to form. ⁠
⁠
My best tip for this is:⁠
⁠
Instead of saying "NEVER" say SOMEDAY.⁠
⁠
Someday could mean never.⁠
⁠
The goal is to FREE the mind from the confines of a box and a label. The goal is to focus on TODAY. What do you REALLY want. Do you want to eat raw food? then choose that. If you have a craving for something random and you are wanting to choose raw, just say "I'll have that someday, some other time, but TODAY I am choosing raw" and then choose that!⁠
⁠
Release the need to hold onto NEVER and just focus one day at a time, choosing what you TRULY want!⁠
⁠

Roots are loaded with minerals, fiber and protein. They are a great addition to a raw diet. Many of these veggies that grow underground are also high in inulin which is a top microbiome food. Things like chicory root, Jerusalem Artickhoke (sunchokes), onions, garlic, jicama and yacon are all great but foods!

Other roots that can be eaten raw include carrots, radishes, beets, parsnips, sweet potatoes, turnips, and more! 

Root veggies are in categories like bulbs (fennel and onion), corms (celery root), rhizomes (ginger, turmeric), tap roots (beets, carrots, parsnips), tuberous roots (sweet potatoes, yucca), and tubers (yams). The bulbs, roots, and tubers absorb water and nutrients to feed the rest of the plant. 

We love roots usually grated in a salad or blended in a wrap base. The high fiber helps hold the wraps together while providing excellent microbiome prebiotics and a high mineral content.

It’s never too late to start! Starting and working on progress is better than never trying just because we want to be “perfect”
We don’t expect t to be fluent in another language overnight. 
Or be able to play intricate pieces of music by heart with a new instrument we just picked up yesterday… 
we understand those things take time and practice… same goes for our new habits! They do NOT change overnight or with one try. They slowly change over time with repetition - the more often you practice a new language, an instrument and YOUR DAILY HABITS, the better you get at them. So just start!
When it comes to a raw vegan diet, people tend to think that if they aren’t 100% perfectly raw RIGHT NOW, then there’s no point in even trying, 
but what if you just started aiming to eat more raw  and make different choices slowly and consistently?
It’s much better to practice and grow than to never try at all because it’s not “the right time” or “it’s too cold here” or “when my partner is on board it’ll be perfect” or “next month I’ll be able to focus more to be perfect” etc.
We don’t need to wait to be perfect.  We have multiple opportunities to make different food choices and practice new habits. The choice is yours.

Never ignore a craving. This doesn’t mean that you just give into it, it means you RECOGNIZE it.⁠
⁠
When you ignore or dismiss a craving, you are missing the whole point of it. A craving is simply a signal your body is giving you because you need fuel. What you crave will be determined by your current habits. We typically crave what we habitually consume and what’s “normal” to et, what’s convenient, what’s easy, what tastes good, or what everyone else is eating. When hungry, we default crave dense calories especially if we have gone long periods without eating, skipped a meal, are consistently under eating, or for other reasons. Recognizing the root of the craving (hunger, boredom, social pressure, stress, etc) will help guide us to what we should choose. ⁠
⁠
So when you crave, recognize it for what it is. A signal. A request. Fill that request with whole plant fuel. Fruit, a smoothie, some nice cream, a giant big salad or whatever fits into your goals for your health.

It’s not boring when it’s what you want.

The goal is to make it what you want. Of course we can want any kind of food but the ultimate driving force behind our choice is our desire. Not just for taste, convenience or to fit in with everyone else, but also for how we feel after the choice. Emotionally and physically. It’s the entire experience of the choice, not just the first 10 minutes. 

How will we feel about ourselves after a healthy choice? Empowered? Balanced? Proud? Confident? Strong? Fulfilled? Librated? Feel these things BEFORE to inspire action. 

Finding joy in choosing our new habits and feeling the feelings we have AFTER we accomplish the habit, can really help to motivate us to actually CHOOSE the new habit. 

We CAN shift our mindsets and motivate ourselves to practice our new habits. Get excited BEFORE about how you are going to feel AFTER!

One of our fave things (other than the raw wraps) is making salads on our tailgate. It’s so empowering to be able to make fresh food wherever we are. 

Travel tips:

1) Grocery stores are your best friends

2) Keep a bin in your vehicle with a knife, solid cutting board, a rag, a jug of water, bowls, forks and any seasoning or spices you may wanna sprinkle onto your salad 

3) If you have an extra bowl, keep a small box of baking soda in your bin too so you can soak and wash produce 

4) Have fun with it! Get all kinds of veggies and even fruits (fresh berries or sliced apple are also wonderful on salads!) and enjoy making something hydrating and fresh. 

5) The best dressing: if you can find a ripe avocado, mix it with mashed tomato and lime juice with chopped fresh herbs! Otherwise, most grocery stores have pre-made guacamole if you’re in a pinch.

Calling all iron seekers! 

If you’re looking for a great source of iron: grow some sunflower microgreens! Just one ounce of sunflower microgreens (which is not even 1 cup chopped!!) has 6 mg of iron!! That’s a stellar amount considering the RDA for men is 8-10mg a day and menstruating women is 18mg! That’s a huge addition to the diet especially if you chopped more than a cup to each salad. 

The iron in animal products is callen heme iron. Heme meaning blood. Non-heme iron from plants is actually safer for humans to consume be a use the body only uptakes what it needs. Heme iron on the other hand, is absorbed indiscriminately which can cause issues with too MUCH iron. 

So get planting today and harvest some delicious sunflower microgreens to add to your daily salads for a great iron boost! Remember, variety is key to a balanced life and we should value each plant for what it can contribute to the puzzle of health.

Filling the hand salad is also an art!

The reason we use dry ingredients like lettuces, cabbage, ribboned carrot, radish, microgreens, red onion etc is because we wrap these for a few days in advance for easy grab lunches on the go or for travel and we want to minimize soggy wraps. 

We don’t use oily mayo or processed spreads (that are usually used on classic wheat or corn wraps) which can be helpful by repelling water from more watery fillings like tomatoes, cucumbers, sauerkraut and pickles so we use a cashew cream cheese spread (recipes in Hand Salads ebook too - link in bio) to help with that aspect (thick enough but oil free!) if we are eating them right away, we put anything in them but if we are wrapping for multiple days, we are conscious of which fillings we add so they stay in tact. 

Then we sauce it up as we eat them. We drizzle a delicious sauce onto each bite and enjoy the flavor explosion of our easy to grab lunch or dinner. It’s a salad you eat… with your hands!

Top 5 quickest tips:

1 • Eat enough calories throughout the day to ensure sustained energy levels and get enough nutrition.
2 • Eat whole plants with minimal processing and highest fiber content.
3 • Eat a wide variety of plants. Aiming for a balance of fruits and greens/veg as both are extremely important.
4 • Focus on low fat so your insulin works well but not NO fat as it’s essential to cell structure and many other things. Aim for more omega 3 rich sources daily and cut back on the unnecessary amount of extra omega 6s. 
5 • Find recipes you love so you can fall back on them when you’re tired, stressed, bored or peer pressured.
6 • Try new things! Explore new recipes, fruits, greens and techniques like sprouting or growing your own food and get out of the typical food habit comforts ones.
7 • Plan your meals out so you know what the day will look like and schedule any prep work in that you’ll need to do for a successful and nourished day.
8 • Always keep learning. We are always evolving and changing. Learn more each day about your body, what you need and work WITH it instead of against it. Perfect doesn’t exist but progress sure doesn’t!

Repeat after me! “I am not in competition with anyone but the me from yesterday.” 

We shouldn’t compare ourselves with anyone. 

It sets us up to feel like failure, struggle with trying to be perfect and we will most likely end up giving up on our new habits. 

You don’t need to be raw for 20 years to feel accomplished and it’s not a contest of who can be the most raw or cleansed etc. We don’t need added pressure in an already challenging life. 

The only thing you need to do is to make better choices than you did yesterday and then keep making those better choices. Focus just one day at a time. Every day is a chance to build your new habits and practice releasing perfectionism.

Be better and do better but not because someone else is, not because you “have to” or out of fear, guilt and regret. Change because YOU want it. Do it because you deserve it.

Just a quick post regarding what’s going on in the news about raw foods and eating disorders. 

I have been speaking out about this in the last few years because I see many people gravitate to raw foods in order to hide a deeper disorder.

Anyone can have an eating disorder on any diet. 

It’s a mental illness. 

About 30 million people suffer with eating disorders and 10,200 die each year from complications and most of them are non-vegan, let alone raw. The sad thing is that raw fruits and vegetables get singled out, but again, most people who have eating disorders aren’t even vegan to begin with but no one says peep about their diets that they followed or the other extreme behaviours they did. 

It’s not veganism or raw food that’s the problem. It’s their relationship with food, their body image and their deep, hidden, unresolved psychological trauma. 98% of people with eating disorders have serious gut issues and 30% have been sexually abused. It goes so much more beyond the food they choose to eat. Let’s zoom out and look at their behaviours and trauma, instead of blaming fruits and veggies. 

There are ways to properly follow vegan and raw vegan diets that nourish, support and grow the body, and there are ultra restrictive and over detoxing ways to do it that deplete and weaken the body further. Fantastic claims, absolute statements and food fears have no place in our healthy food choices and aren’t helpful to our mental health. 

My goal here is to inspire and support a healthy, fun way to eat more raw foods and that you don’t have to be 100% raw. The goal is always to eat adequate calories, eat a very wide variety of plants, and learn to discern between balance and extremes, to avoid falling to the votex of over detoxing and extreme cleansing or restrictively “simple” protocols. 

Testing yourself regularly is important. Blood, omega, microbiome, etc. Learn about your body and it’s needs, supplement if necessary. If you or a loved one is struggling, reach out for professional help and keep an open heart. It could save a life and it’s a long road to recovery.

“Discernment is the ability to see things for what they really are instead of what you wish or want them to be.” ~ said a smart person out there who I heard this from once…. 

There is so much misinformation out there confusing everyone. Learning how to discern between realistic statements and fantastic theoretical statements can help guide us to balance and truth instead of extremes and unmet expectations. 

This is why I really strive to not use absolute statements in what I post. It’s super important to me that I share things in an appropriate way without having to use an absolute statement just to get my point across. I hope this is helpful to others to navigate the sea of health advice out there, as I don’t want to be part of the excessive overuse of these cringy tactics. 

As someone with a large account here on social media I feel a deep responsibility to practice integrity when I share content. Click bait and confidence can easily sell an idea or theory, but honesty and truth are far more important to me above all else. 

I do not know everything and never will, just like all of us. Being humble, continuing to learn, expand and evolve with new information instead of clinging to old ideas is top priority for me in my growth and I want to thank everyone who has supported and loved me through this whole adventure with raw foods. I see you. I appreciate you. I believe in YOU!

“Lissa, regular corn taco shells are still vegan, why are yours so different?”

• Store-bought taco shells are baked or fried in oil. Ours are not. 

• Store-bought taco shells are made using high omega 6 rich pro inflammatory oils. Ours are made with a small amount of anti inflammatory omega 3 rich ground flax.

• Store-bought taco shells are about the same calorically but ours are higher in both protein and fiber because we aren’t using oils. 

• Most store-bought taco shells are loaded with sodium. Many having roughly 200mg/shell. Ours only have 50mg/shell or as low as 6mg/shell if you leave out the miso paste. 

• Ours have added flavor bonuses too like jalapeño, onion, garlic or chili powder if you like!

• Ours are raw and dehydrated instead of baked or fried.

• You can even add some ground turmeric for bonus nutrients and anti inflammatory properties

• Ours are homemade. It’s empowering to make your own food. You can also make them with heirloom and organic corn in season if you can find for extra bonus awesomeness. You can also make them different colours based on what you add like tomato and chili powder or greens powder and cilantro!

• They still crunch just right!

Are you sprouting?!

Some of our top fave things to sprout:

• lentils of all kinds (beluga, crimson, green, French, brown, etc) 
• mung beans and peas
• seeds like broccoli, radish, cabbage, kale, clover, alfalfa, fenugreek, etc

Super easy!

Grab a mason jar and something mesh like for the lid. You can buy sprouting lids or just use a fine mesh with elastic band. 

Choose your seed or lentil etc. put about 2tbsp up to 1/4 cup of dry seeds into the jar and soak in water for 12 hour or so. 

After the initial soak, rinse and drain 2-3x a day for 3-5 days and you’ll have sprouts! When ready to eat, transfer to the fridge and use within 2-3 days. Eat them up! Don’t forget about them!!

The number one reason why people struggle on raw is because they just don’t eat enough, even if they truly think they intuitively are.

Raw foods are very low calorie density so one must eat MUCH more of them to get adequate nutrition and energy. If you aren’t eating enough from fruits and veggies, you’ll default to craving high fat calories from nuts/avocado etc or denser other calories from a variety of sources.

Hunger is natural. It doesn’t need to be controlled or avoided. It needs to be honoured. Cravings are a signal that you’re hungry. We typically crave what we HABITUALLY choose. We choose what’s convenient, tasty, “normal”, easy, fast, what we are used to, what comforts us, and what everyone else is choosing.

If we can change what we choose when hungry, we can effectively change our craving then we are hungry.

I will say it again. Hunger is normal. Anyone on any diet will get hungry. The question is… what will you honour your hunger with?!

When cruciferous veggies are chopped, blended or chewed, they release the enzyme myrosinase which interacts with the glucosinolates in the plant and creates sulphoraphane! The incredible compound responsible for many benefits in the human body. 

Myrosinase is very sensitive to heat so it needs time to do it’s job. It’s recommended to chop broccoli small (more chops = more myrosinase) and let it sit for 45 mins before cooking if you do cook it to get the most benefits. 

We eat it raw so don’t worry about the 45 mins but it’s good to know if it needs to be cooked. 

We love our cruciferous and aim to have some every day in any form. Cabbage, shredded Brussels sprouts, broccoli, cauliflower, radishes, and the sprouts from these seeds. There are many more too! Which are your fave cruciferous?!

So we go to the market a little late and just catch them closing up for the day. I really wanted some juicy heirlooms because it’s the season right now and they were looking amazing. I was completely 100% ready and willing, fully prepared to happily spend quite a bit on these lovelies. 

I started filling a few bags of tomatoes, they were just too beautiful, I couldn’t stop choosing! I started imagining eating massive tomato salads with a little cucumber, lettuce and red onion with my French dressing. My mouth was tingling with excitement. After filling the 3 bags, I was ready to pay but didn’t wanna carry them so I asked, “could I have one of the empty boxes to carry them as it would be easier to take them home to Las Vegas” 

Dude said, “Yeah just take a box and fill it up!” So I started to fill it with the tomatoes we chose and a couple more. I was ready… this was gonna be good! 

I look over at him as he was packing up for the day, his scale was nowhere in sight so I asked, “okay I’m ready, how much will these be?!” And he said, “just fill the box and take it, don’t worry about it”

I was stunned. I asked 3x if he was sure, and he said yeah if you’re gonna take that many just take it! Nate gave him a massive hug and we left with around 30lbs of organic heirlooms. 

2 things I learned: 

- Good intentions can bring epic surprises
- Go to the market at the very last minute closing, you never know what farmers will give away! 

Have you ever scored free food at the end of the market?! If so, what was it? Share in the comments!

There’s always something we can make!

What I d found over the last 9 years is that when you start choosing different things, it gets easier and easier to keep choosing those things. I never believed it, but habits do indeed change. Default choices DO change when you take an active role in changing your choices. 

It just takes time and I never had the patience to give myself the time I needed to change until I went raw. My weekly and daily menu options shifted and over time became new default options. It’s super easy to choose raw now for me because I have built super strong habits over the years. 

If you’re struggling, here are some tips that helped me:

• Always eat enough. If you under eat, miss or skip a meal, it’s gonna be super extra challenging to work through current habits default choices

• Find your “Fallback 5” which is 5 quick and easy healthy recipes that you LOVE that you can “fall back on” when you’re in a hungry mood

• Keep exploring recipes. Might might now totally enjoy some, but others you’ll love! Don’t give up. Even after you’re established and things are good, continue to try new recipes! You’re Fallback 5 and other menu faves will shift as you discover new meal ideas. 

• Default to fruit. It’s hard to think straight when you’re hungry and craving. Grab some fruit and eat a bunch first before contemplating other options. Usually you’ll feel better and think clearer so you can choose something else that’s more aligned with your goals.

Happy World Vegan Day!

Veganism is not a diet. Diet does play a large role within veganism, but veganism is so much more than just what we eat. It’s an ethical stand against the exploitation of animals. There is no perfect vegan either. We get that. Being a human is destructive in so many ways but as a vegan we choose to do the LEAST amount of harm that we can. Clothing, personal care items, entertainment (not going to zoos etc), home care products and of course food, are all part of it. 

Since going vegan in 2014, my entire life is different. Health, love, relationships, career, where I live and how I think and feel are all so different now and I wouldn’t change it. It can be lonely and Vystopic (read Vystopia by Clare Mann) as a vegan in a non vegan world, but it’s what fuels my passion and what feels right to me.

Microbiome ferments!

Here is the recipe for the watermelon radish “kimchi” style pro-gut ferment! This recipe made 3 gallons plus 1 quart. You’ll need glass fermenting weights and air lock lids to make them. I split this recipe over 2 large mixing bowls to make it easier to mix. 

3 heads of Napa cabbage
5 lbs watermelon radishes (or other)
1 large Korean radish
2 cups of grated sunchokes
3 cups grated carrots
2 medium red onion, thinly sliced
6 tbsp non-iodized sea salt (3 tbsp per bowl - or to taste)
15 hot Thai chilis (or less to preference)
3 tbsp gocugaru flakes
2 tsp red pepper flakes
1/4 cup freshly grated garlic
1/4 cup freshly grated ginger
1 cup lemon juice
4 tbsp date sugar (from @thedatelady split 2 tbsp per bowl)

1 - Take 4 leaves off the cabbage to use as toppers. Thinly slice the cabbage and matchstick all of the radishes. Slice the red onion and grate the sunchokes and carrots. Place everything in the bowl or bowls and add the salt. With clean hands massage the mix for a couple minutes until soft. Cover bowl(s) with a towel and let sit for 30 mins

2 - Once super soft, add the date sugar, lemon juice, garlic, ginger, gochugaru, red pepper flakes and hot chilies into the bowl(s) and mix again with hands. 

3 - Stuff mason jars with mix and liquid until almost full (where the glass bends) add a cabbage leaf to the top and more liquid only if needed. Forcefully press a glass weight into the jar so EVERYTHING is fully submerged. Leave about an inch of space from the rim. Top with an airlock lid and allow to ferment for 1-2 weeks. Once ready, taste and transfer to the fridge with a normal lid. Eat and enjoy in meals!

Salads are super important for us to get loads of fiber variety, minerals, protein and antioxidants but just the greens and veggies are so low calorie that we need something to help boost calories and get bonus nutrition…

In comes the dressing!

Home made raw dressings are excellent ways to get the needed calories into a raw salad as well as a ton of bonus nutrients. We start with a fruit base (this one is mango but we usually use dates) and add onto the dressing with things like ground chia for omega 3, garlic, lemon juice, onion powder, spicy stuff like chilies and jalapeño, ginger, fresh herbs and anything else we feel we want to add. Our dressings are always oil free and if we use fats, they are whole sources like nuts, seeds, avocado or young coconut. 

We then drown our salads with the entire batch of dressing to not only deliver epic flavor, but needed whole food calories and bonus nutrition and fiber.

When I’m preparing food lately, I think of my future self, which will soon be my present self. Will I want a wrap on a long car drive?! Will I be happy we chopped those salads the night before a super busy day? Will I be grateful I took 10 minutes to marinate my veggies a few hours before dinner? 

Of course! 

Thinking of my future self helps motivate me to get prep done. Wether it’s 10 seconds in the morning to soak some nuts for dinner, or taking the time to rinse and drain sprouts, or even taking the time the night before to blend up the wraps so we have deliciousness the next day. 

I’m always grateful for the things my past self did that help me in the present moment. We are so disconnected from our future selves because we live in the present so much and our choices are made right now. Cultivating a connection with my future self and working to make my future easier in the present has been so rewarding! 

I hope you can work on that too!

Some might think how I eat
is very limited…

But I eat WAY more variety of different plant foods now than I ever have in my entire life.
I eat more things that I have never eaten before and I’m consistent with getting a wide variety.
It feels amazing!

The illusion of variety with the standard foods is more shape and technique rather than abundance of variety. I ate wheat in countless different shapes and ways… but it was still all wheat. I ate salt and fat in many ways too but it was just still salt and fat. I ate the same few ingredients over and over, just prepared differently to create an illusion of variety. Now I ACTUALLY eat variety and it’s been delicious and good to me and my microbiome! 

Next time you’re at the store, step out of the staples you usually buy and ADD a couple new things! Haven’t had bok choy in a while? Get it! See something seasonal? Get it? Usually only buy alfalfa sprouts? Get the broccoli too! Expand your variety by choosing it for yourself! Normally get green cabbage? Try purple this time! Don’t know what to do with radishes? Get some anyways and add thinly sliced to a salad!

Eating food together is such an important part of social health but what we choose to eat plays a big role in our personal health too.

We don’t HAVE to eat what everyone else eats, but being together and spending quality time together is very important. Communication is key when choosing differently that the people we eat with. It’s always wonderful when the food aligns with our goals but that isn’t always the case…

We always try to remember that our choices in social settings is just that. Our choice. If others have issues with that choice, thats usually just their insecurities showing themselves. They may feel threatened, abandoned, not wanting to change themselves and not wanting YOU to change either. This can create tension simply because you choose to eat something different at the table. But it’s also YOUR body and if something doesn’t resonate with you, you do not have to eat it to fit in. Most tension can be relaxed either live and reassurance. It’s a tough situation to be in for sure but finding balance between your personal goals and choices and being part of the group is an ongoing evolution project. Keep at it! Be the example you want to see in the world.

My fave quote for this year:

“You don’t get results by focusing on the results. You get results by focusing on the habits and behaviour that produce the results!”

Become the type of person who does the things that you will need to be doing every day to get the results that that type of person would have. 

Wanna be an athlete? What do athletes do each day? They train. Do that. 
Wanna be a pianist? What do pianists do each day? They practice. Do that.
Wanna be vegan? What do vegans choose each day? They choose plants at every meal. Do that. 
Wanna speak a new language? What do people who speak that language do each day? They speak it. Do that?! 

Do the things that get you the results. Focus on THOSE things instead of the result. The result will come from doing the things. 

Happy 2024 everyone!

Many people have mentioned that the wraps look dry or that we don’t have sauce. 

We don’t add sauce into the wrap unless we are eating them right away. Most of the time, we wrap wraps in advance for multiple days (I love a wrap the next day after wrapping - it’s my fave) so we fill the wraps without the sauce and without wet ingredients like tomatoes, cucumbers, pickles, sauerkraut, etc for two reasons:

When I learned that it’s actually ACTION that creates motivation and inspiration and not inspiration and motivation that create action …

… my life changed

Action starts the ball rolling. No matter what that is. It could be as small of an action as getting off the couch and walking into the kitchen to make a meal. Or just doing one squat. Or just picking up the apple, even if you don’t really want it and want to eat cookies. Just little actions can springboard motivation and inspiration. 

We often get overwhelmed with the entire process but usually once we start, it begins to flow. Many times I don’t feel like making a salad (because I’m human) but just the simple act of taking a few things out of the fridge is enough to start me. By the time I grab the knife and a bowl, I’m getting into a flow that I’m super grateful that I did AFTER the salad is made and I have something delicious and refreshing to eat. 

Same goes for working on anything. Just start with one line of text if you’re writing, open the design app if you’re designing. Learn one word of a new language if you’re learning it. Just do something, it most times brings motivation to keep going!
