I get my protein from all the plants I eat. 

Eating a variety of plants provides all the amino acids (including all 9 essential ones) to build the body. The myth that a plant based diet is incomplete was retracted and disproved over 20 yrs ago but it still sadly continues to be used today to try and convince people that a vegan diet lacks protein. 

Just because one type of plant might be lower in or lack an amino acid does NOT mean that a plant based diet is incomplete. Think about it. Sure if we only ate one type of food for every meal for the rest of our life, we might create a deficiency - but that’s just not reality. In reality we eat a variety of things which naturally covers our needs if we eat enough. 

Why are we continuing to perpetuate an old and incorrect theory? For one, it validates certain opposing opinions and theories and second, because old content, ideas and theories usually are not updated or taken down. People still find it and if it’s “old” it somehow holds wisdom even if it’s been disproven long ago as well… Even old books are still in circulation, despite new books and research proving them incorrect. Myths continue because old theories are not updated and people still take them at face value today instead of digging into the new research and challenging these old beliefs. 

I’m certainly not worried about protein. I increase my weights I lift in the gym often, which means I’m getting stronger, which means I’m building muscle… on raw plants. 

A better question would be…where’s the fiber variety! Society is so focused on getting enough protein when only around 3% of people get their RDA of fiber a day…🤔 

Also remember… when we under eat, our bodies break down muscle too so EAT enough!

That’s right! Everything I eat has protein in it already. I don’t need to focus on eating certain things to get more of it. I already get more than enough for my needs. 

Protein is found in all plant foods (except oil, which is 100% fat and which I don’t use anyways). Plants have different amounts of it, yes, but they all have it. Fruits, greens, vegetables, nuts and seeds, sprouts and microgreens… even herbs have a little! Amino acids are part of everything and my main focus is just 2 things:

1) Eat enough calories to cover basic needs (BMR) plus all other activity during the day (talking, walking, thinking, working, exercising, errands, and all other activities) 
2) Eat variety. A wide variety. I’m not into the diet simplicity of only eating a few different foods. Variety is key not only to get the broadest range of nutrition, but also to give our guts the most fiber. Greens, sprouts and veg are just as important as fruit. 

Fiber may not be a building block, but there are 38 trillion bacteria in our guts that are also ESSENTIAL for our health, digestion, vitamin extraction, immunity, mood, and more. And Fiber is THEIR food. I feel fiber is far too often brushed aside cuz it’s not “a building block” but it’s still essential to human health via the gut microbiome and digestion. 

An actual protein deficiency is pretty rare and usually happens with people on ANY diet who consistently under eat. Even people still eating meat can lose muscle mass if they don’t eat enough and don’t exercise enough and plant protein can easily build muscle just fine, as found in many recent studies. It’s important to dive into NEW research instead of continuing to parrot the same older info that’s no longer valid.

My biggest learning curve was to make sure that I always ate enough because a half tank of gas quickly becomes an empty one!

Many times in my past I would think, “oh I’m not that hungry, I’ll just wait” instead of topping up my tank with a meal. I’d usually get busy with something and suddenly my tank was completely empty and I was ravenous!!! I learned that I have to eat more often to satiate instead of letting my tank run dry and start looking for anything and everything to fill it. That yo-yo wasn’t fun and I always felt heavy mood swings and cravings. Eating more often and filling my tank back up when it was half full was a big key to my success with changing habits. We do not have to wait until we are hungry to eat. We also do not have to wait until we are thirsty to drink water. In fact thirst is usually a sign you’re already dehydrated. So why wait? I much prefer a consistent supply of energy to keep my mind sharp and focused, my moods stable and my energy levels high! 

It’s very easy to understand eat on a raw or even just a vegan diet and when we under eat, over time this can bring issues. Eating enough calories AND variety of nutrition helps us stay balanced!

I really need to share this today…

Eating “LESS calories for longevity” DOES NOT MEAN eating less than WHAT YOU NEED!!!!! 

Far too many people cut calories because someone online said to eat less calories to live longer. Most people are already not eating enough, and restricting further is NOT the answer. 

When people say to EAT LESS CALORIES FOR LONGEVITY, they are ACTUALLY simply saying to NOT OVER EAT what you need. They do not mean to eat less than your needs. 

And on that note, your NEEDS are not just your BMR. That’s your bare minimum requirement. You need a lot more than that number especially if you wanna build or maintain muscle and stay strong. It’s actually your BMR + all activity. If you are not covering both your BMR AND your total activity (walking, talking, working, moving, exercising, errands, playing, basically everything!) then your body compensates by turning its muscle and fat into energy. This could mean an extra 600-1000+ calories ABOVE your BMR!!!! Plus under eating is also nutrient restriction. People who under eat on ANY diet also risk losing muscle mass and leaning towards deficiencies over time. Eat please!

So next time we hear “eat less calories for longevity” it actually means “eat the appropriate amount of healthy whole food calories instead of over eating on high calorie/processed foods” 

The longevity studies were NOT about restriction. When they say “restricting” they just meant that the people noticing the benefits were limited to an APPROPRIATE amount of calories for their body needs beyond BMR instead of the other group who was free to over eat their needs. In another study they showed that people who ate less than their needs did NOT get the longevity benefits of the theory. Gotta eat appropriate amounts for your body. Like Goldilocks, not too little and not too much…. Get it JUST RIGHT! Let’s ditch diet culture restriction and enjoy an abundance of healthy options. 

Thanks for listening to my rant!

Iron! 

Did you know that in ONE CUP of sunflower microgreens (1 ounce) there’s around 6mg of iron?! 

For perspective:
Men and postmenopausal women need around 8mg a day
Menstruating women need around 18mg a day 

Pictured in the reel is 1 ounce which is roughly one cup chopped. With everything else we eat each day, it’s super easy to get adequate iron because we eat a wide variety of plants. 

Other great raw vegan sources include all other leafy greens, beets, sprouted lentils and chickpeas, dried apricots, all cruciferous vegetables like broccoli, mushrooms, cashews, natto, unpasteurized tempeh, almonds, flax, tomatoes all types fresh, sundried and and tomato powder, sweet potatoes (put them raw in the wraps!), mulberries, black olives, dried thyme and sprouted oats! 

Sprouting and fermenting foods makes iron more available as well hence why sprouting lentils is a great option. Make sure to include vitamin C rich foods with iron rich ones to enhance absorption as well.

Before doing anything, I’m getting into the habit of asking myself, will this help support my goals or bring joy to my day?

Obviously we are still human and not everything we do is product rive or brings joy, but really questioning certain things is helping to discern between what is helping me and what is hindering me. 

Questioning our current habits and re-evaluating what we could do instead that can support us and/or bring joy can expose what we think we need to do vs what we WANT to be doing. Shifting perspective and getting excited about building consistency is much more fulfilling long term than the quick fixes and dopamine hits we get by justifying habits that no longer serve our well being. 

What are YOU working on in the habit department lately?!
